==English==
===Etymology===
Shortened from {{m|en|Yankee}}.
===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|en|/jæŋk/}}
* {{audio|en|en-au-Yank.ogg|Audio (AU)}}
* {{rhymes|en|æŋk|s=1}}
===Noun===
{{wikipedia|Yankee}}
{{en-noun}}
# {{lb|en|US}} A [[Yankee]], a [[Northerner]]: someone from the Northern United States, especially from [[New England]].
#* '''1865''', unnamed Confederate officer, according to Lieutenant Joseph E. Moody, U.S.V., “Life in Confederate Prisons”, in ''Civil War Papers'', Volume II, Massachusetts Commandery (1900), [http://books.google.com/books?id=d7RYAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA368&dq=Yanks page 368]:
#*: Halt! come down there, you '''Yanks''', come down!
#* '''1944''', [[w:Howard Fast|Howard Fast]], ''Freedom Road'', M.E. Sharpe (1995), {{ISBN|978-1-56324-440-7}}, [http://books.google.com/books?id=S-fOlzPO400C&pg=PA33&dq=yanks page 33]:
#*: “I do wish I might of found you in my sights when you was with them damn '''Yanks''',” Abner added.
#* '''2004''', O. K. Williams, ''The Way the Cards Fall'', Trafford Publishing, {{ISBN|9781412022897}}, [http://books.google.com/books?id=XvanTnXFtxwC&pg=PA16&dq=Yanks page 16]:
#*: Corporal Bob explained, “The '''Yanks''' has tha best weapons. But us Rebs know how to shoot tha damn things. {{...}}”
# {{lb|en|slang|Australia|New Zealand|Ireland|Canada|United Kingdom|sometimes|pejorative}} An [[American]]: someone from the [[United States]].
#* '''1951''', “The '''Yanks''' Are Coming: U.S. shows world we are playing for keeps as 4th Division leaves to join Eisenhower's NATO army”, in ''[[w:Life (magazine)|Life]]'', 11 June 1951, [http://books.google.com/books?id=c1EEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA38&dq=Yanks page 38]:
#*: “This time,” he [<nowiki/>[[w:Alphonse Juin|General Alphonse-Pierre Juin]]] told the '''Yanks''', “you have not crossed to win new victories but to preserve peace. {{...}}”
